{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474753","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474753"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:24:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:24:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12391"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12391","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12391"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.41,0.07,0.07,0.21,0.25]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4901"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"33611"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4901","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4901"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12391"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"18952"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"570"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6281"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7987"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8502"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"33611","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/33611"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 5-year-old boy is brought to the Emergency Department by his parents because of localised left elbow swelling and pain (8/10). His parents mention that about one hour ago he fell from his bike, landed on an outstretched arm and has not been able to move his elbow since. On examination his range of motion at the elbow is limited by pain throughout, with obvious bruising, swelling, and tenderness on palpation of the elbow. An X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following findings would be most common in this type of injury?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Absent radial pulse","Inability to abduct shoulder","Pain at anatomical snuffbox","Radial deviation of the wrist","Absent proximal brachial pulse"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe X-ray of the left elbow shows a supracondylar humeral fracture with anterior displacement of the proximal fragment. The most likely abnormal physical sign would be \u003Cstrong\u003Eabsence of the radial pulse. \u003C/strong\u003EThe brachial artery passes immediately anteriorly to the distal humerus and is commonly injured with anterior displacement. The brachial artery forms the radial artery as it travels distally. The absence of the radial pulse occurs in up to 12% of supracondylar fractures. In addition, there would also be significant localised swelling and bruising in the antecubital fossa with possible skin puckering due to the displaced proximal fragment button-holing through the bracialis muscle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInability to abduct the shoulder \u003C/strong\u003Eis linked to axillary nerve damage, which innervates the deltoid muscle. It is too proximal from the distal humerus to be damaged by a supracondylar fracture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETenderness at the anatomical snuffbox\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with scaphoid fractures, typically when falling onto an outstretched hand during a fall. However, the X-ray shows that there is a more sinister pathology of a supracondylar fracture with anterior displacement, with his symptoms localised to his elbow and none at his wrist. Whilst concurrent distal radius fracture is not uncommon, concurrent scaphoid fracture is not a recognised associated injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadial deviation of the wrist \u003C/strong\u003Eis due to ulnar nerve damage, which is possible but rare with supracondylar fractures. Ulnar nerve damage would also cause claw hand phenomenon (flexion of the 4th and 5th digits) and finger spreading. Ulnar nerve damage is usually associated with medial displacement of the distal humerus in supracondylar fractures, as the nerve passes through the cubital tunnel at the elbow. However, the elbow X-ray (left image) shows distinct anterior displacement. Although nerve injury occurs in up to 11% of extension type supracondylar fractures, the most commonly damage nerve is the median nerve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbsent proximal brachial pulse\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely due to the more distal nature of the fracture. The brachial artery is a continuation of the axillary artery, which passes below the teres major muscle and is significantly more proximal from the distal humerus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENote: Anterior interosseous nerve palsy (terminal motor branch of median nerve) is the most commonly injured structure in supracondylar fractures with anterior displacement of the proximal fragment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESupracondylar fractures can be classified according to the mechanism of injury - Flexion type, and the much commoner extension type (~97%).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Gartland classification is most commonly used to guide management of supracondylar humeral fractures \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The important neurovascular structures surrounding the distal humerus are the brachial artery, median nerve, radial nerve, and ulnar nerve.","The ulnar nerve is commonly injured (5%) in flexion type supracondylar humerus fractures but rare in extension type fractures.","The Gartland classification (Type I-III) is used to guide management of supracondylar humeral fractures"],"references":["Vaquero-Picado A, Gonz\u00e1lez-Mor\u00e1n G, Moraleda L. Management of supracondylar fractures of the humerus in children. EFORT open reviews. 2018 Oct 1;3(10):526-40.","Kumar V, Singh A. Fracture supracondylar humerus: a review. Journal of clinical and diagnostic research: JCDR. 2016 Dec;10(12):RE01."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"18952"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12391"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19471"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19472"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19471"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f3b2c386-4fd7-4b0c-b7d2-833c68623a5e.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f3b2c386-4fd7-4b0c-b7d2-833c68623a5e.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":656,"height":750}},{"type":"media","id":"19472","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19472"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/80db3590-b3e4-42bb-824e-28a6776ec23d.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/80db3590-b3e4-42bb-824e-28a6776ec23d.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":502,"height":349}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"18952","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/18952"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-03-15T00:26:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2023-03-15T00:26:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4901"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"33611"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"typ